Searching means finding something in a list or collection.

ğŸ§© Types of Searching
There are mainly two main types of searching in programming:
  1. Linear Search (Sequential Search)
         ğŸ‘‰ Check each element one by one until you find the target.
         Example:
              List: 5, 8, 2, 9, 1
              Search for: 9
         Steps:
                Check 5 âŒ
                Check 8 âŒ
                Check 2 âŒ
                Check 9 âœ… Found it!
         Time complexity: O(n)
   2. Binary Search :
                 ğŸ‘‰ Works only on sorted lists either in ascending or descending.Itâ€™s much faster than linear search.
       For Ascending How it works:
                             Find the middle element
                             If itâ€™s the number â†’ âœ… Found
                             If the number is smaller, search in left half
                             If bigger, search in right half
                  Example:
                         Sorted list: 1, 3, 5, 7, 9, 11, 13
                         Search: 9
                  Steps:
                        Middle = 7 â†’ 9 is bigger â†’ search right side
                        Right side: 9, 11, 13 â†’ middle = 11 â†’ 9 is smaller â†’ search left
                        Found 9 âœ…
         Time complexity: O(log n)
Note:-
for finding mid ,
ğŸ‘‰ Formula: mid = (lowIndx + highIndx) / 2;   -> might cause integer overflow (go beyond integer limit). so below formula use
ğŸ‘‰ Safe Formula:  mid = lowIndx + (highIndx - lowIndx) / 2;


